Mini Project 2: Breast Cancer Dataset¶

Matthew Martin¶

Intro¶

Problem Statement¶

This project explores the breast cancer gene expression dataset GSE45827 from the CuMiDa database, which includes 151 tissue samples and 54,676 gene expression features. The dataset represents 5 breast cancer subtypes and normal tissue.

Due to the extremely high dimensionality of gene expression data, we apply Principal Component Analysis (PCA) for dimensionality reduction, to extract the dominant patterns of variance and visualize sample clustering.

Our goals:

  • Understand patterns in gene expression that differentiate cancer subtypes.
  • Use PCA and clustering to explore unsupervised structure in the data.
  • Investigate which genes contribute most to principal components.
  • Validate clustering results against known subtype labels.

This analysis may inform biomarker discovery or subtype classification strategies in cancer genomics.

EDA Results¶

Are these gene expressions correlated?¶

Gene 205916_at and 202917_s_at are highly correlated, 228241_at is correlated with 209173_at, as well as 205009_at. This is supported by the correlation matrix, where we observe high correlation coefficients among some top genes, suggesting they may be co-expressed or regulated by the same biological process.

Which genes vary most across cancer subtypes?¶

Among the top genes with the highest variance, we observe that genes like 206378_at, 228241_at, and 205916_at show clear differences in expression across subtypes, as seen in boxplots. This suggests they may play a role in subtype-specific gene regulation.

Is there any observed skew or outliers?¶

Most gene expression values are concentrated between 0–5, indicating left-skewed distributions. Some outliers are present, especially in basal and HER2+ subtypes, which could reflect true biological differences or batch effects.

data transformation decsion¶

We scale the data using StandardScaler because PCA and clustering algorithms are sensitive to feature magnitudes. Without scaling, genes with larger absolute values would dominate the principal components.

We do not apply log transformation here because the data appears already normalized and log-like. No missing values are present, so no imputation is required.

We also exclude metadata columns (samples, type) to ensure PCA operates only on gene expression values.

Clustering¶

I perform K-means clustering on the PCA-transformed data using the first 20 principal components as features. I am just usiong the first 20 to avoid the curse of dimensionality which causes methodologies like k- means to be less effective.

Since the dataset has 6 unique labels, I start by setting the number of clusters k = 6.

In [75]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
k = 6
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
clusters_kmeans = kmeans.fit_predict(X_pca[:, :20])  
print("K-means cluster assignments:")
print(clusters_kmeans)
score_kmeans = silhouette_score(X_pca[:, :20], clusters_kmeans)
print(f"Silhouette Score (K-means, k={k}): {score_kmeans:.4f}")

Hierarchical¶

Next, since the score is relatively low I will perform hierarchical clustering using Ward’s linkage on the same PCA components.

In [79]:
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import linkage, dendrogram, fcluster
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

Z = linkage(X_pca[:, :20], method='ward')

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
dendrogram(Z)

plt.show()

clusters_hier = fcluster(Z, t=k, criterion='maxclust')

score_hier = silhouette_score(X_pca[:, :20], clusters_hier)
print(f"Silhouette Score (Hierarchical, k={k}): {score_hier:.4f}")

Silhouette Score (Hierarchical, k=6): 0.1913

Hierarchical clustering achieved a silhouette score of 0.1913 for k=6, while K-means achieved 0.1941. For six clusters, K-means did a bit better than hierarchical clustering on silhouette score, meaning its clusters are a little tighter.

HyperParameterTuning to get a better clustering score¶

Since neither the k=6 k means clustering or hierachial returned an impressive score I will perform hyoperparameter tuning to attempt to find better parameters.

In [68]:
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import linkage, fcluster
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
import numpy as np

best_k = None
best_score = -1 
scores = []

Z = linkage(X_pca[:, :20], method='ward')  
for k in range(2, 26):  # start from 2 clusters
    clusters = fcluster(Z, t=k, criterion='maxclust')
    score = silhouette_score(X_pca[:, :20], clusters)
    print("score, num of clusters",(score,k))
    scores.append(score)
    if score > best_score:
        best_score = score
        best_k = k

print(f"Best number of clusters: {best_k} with silhouette score: {best_score:.4f}")

I was looking for a way to compare the strength of the labeling and used generative AI to get ARI and NMI as methods for doing so. The Adjusted Rand Index (ARI) evaluates how well the clustering matches the true subtypes while accounting for chance, and the Normalized Mutual Information (NMI) measures the shared information between the cluster assignments and the actual classes. Using these metrics allows me to assess the quality of the unsupervised clustering, confirming that hierarchical clustering performed slightly better than KMeans in capturing the underlying biological structure.

In [77]:
from sklearn.metrics import adjusted_rand_score, normalized_mutual_info_score
# Adjusted Rand Index (ARI) and Normalized Mutual Information (NMI) 
# assess clustering quality compared to known labels, adjusted for chance.

# KMeans 
ari_k = adjusted_rand_score(df['type'], clusters_kmeans)
nmi_k = normalized_mutual_info_score(df['type'], clusters_kmeans)

# Hierarchical 
ari_h = adjusted_rand_score(df['type'], clusters_hier )
nmi_h = normalized_mutual_info_score(df['type'], clusters_hier )

print("KMeans ARI:", ari_k, "NMI:", nmi_k)
print("Hierarchical ARI:", ari_h, "NMI:", nmi_h)

KMeans ARI: 0.39140885486841964 NMI: 0.6004892775812123
Hierarchical ARI: 0.42634557385473565 NMI: 0.6331513458579441

Results¶

  • PCA reduced the dimensionality of the dataset from 151 features to 105 components while preserving 90% of the variance.

  • K-means (k=6) yielded a silhouette score of 0.194, relatively weak separation.

  • Hierarchical clustering (k=6) performed similarly with a score of 0.191.

  • Hyperparameter tuning (k=2 to 25) for hierarchical clustering showed the best result at k=2, achieving a score of 0.329, the highest overall.

  • ARI ~0.4-0.43 and NMI ~0.6-0.63 means the clustering lines up moderately well with the known subtype labels

Discussion¶

  • The relatively low silhouette scores for both K-means and hierarchical clustering (except for k=2 in hierarchical) indicate weak cluster structure in the dataset.

  • The PCA projection may reduce noise, but the original data likely contains overlapping subtypes, instead of distinct subtypes or groups.

  • The peak score at k=2 is most likely due to the model easily being able to distinguish between cancerous and noncancerous samples and is most likely not reflective of the best number of clustering groups.

  • K-means has a slightly better silhouette score, which means its clusters are a bit tighter. But hierarchical clustering scores higher on ARI and NMI, meaning its clusters match the true labels better. So, even though K-means looks cleaner, hierarchical clustering groups the data in a way that fits the actual cancer subtypes more accurately.

Conclusion¶

  • PCA effectively reduced the dimensionality while preserving important variance

  • Hierarchical clustering performed better than K-means for this data, especially at k=2, but overall, clustering performance was moderate.

  • Clustering based on just gene expression may not fully capture the complexity of the biological subtypes structure, additional features or supervised methods could help improve classification

  • Future work could explore t-SNE/UMAP, or ensemble clustering
